WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.730 --> 00:00:02.120
How does factoring relate to

2
00:00:02.140 --> 00:00:05.073
determining whether expressions are equivalent?

3
00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:08.760
Think about this question during a lesson.

4
00:00:11.030 --> 00:00:14.350
Kiana is painting an ocean mural on a rectangular wall.

5
00:00:16.039 --> 00:00:18.630
To start, she painted the wall blue.

6
00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:22.390
She used three cans of paint,

7
00:00:22.503 --> 00:00:25.050
each of which covered x square meters,

8
00:00:25.300 --> 00:00:28.770
and a different sized can that covered 12 square meters.

9
00:00:30.770 --> 00:00:31.750
What are the possible

10
00:00:31.774 --> 00:00:34.336
length and height dimensions of Kiana's mural?

11
00:00:36.340 --> 00:00:40.670
The expression three x plus 12 represents the area of the mural.

12
00:00:43.630 --> 00:00:46.379
One way to solve this problem is with an area model.

13
00:00:49.440 --> 00:00:52.560
You can use an area model to represent the area of the mural,

14
00:00:52.779 --> 00:00:54.620
three times x plus 12.

15
00:00:56.683 --> 00:00:59.040
The first part of the area model represents

16
00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:01.260
the area covered by the three cans of paint.

17
00:01:04.056 --> 00:01:05.300
The second part represents

18
00:01:05.300 --> 00:01:08.809
the 12 square meters, the large can of paint covered.

19
00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:13.789
Now we can look for possible dimensions of the wall being painted.

20
00:01:14.450 --> 00:01:17.390
How can you use algebra tiles to represent the expression?

21
00:01:20.630 --> 00:01:23.180
There’s three cans times x,

22
00:01:23.460 --> 00:01:25.855
the number of square meters each can covered.

23
00:01:28.459 --> 00:01:31.263
The other can covered 12 square meters.

24
00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:35.470
We can think of that as three times four.

25
00:01:37.370 --> 00:01:40.509
So one possible set of dimensions of the mural could be

26
00:01:40.559 --> 00:01:43.549
x plus four meters long and three meters tall.

27
00:01:47.090 --> 00:01:50.710
You can also solve this problem by using a common factor and

28
00:01:50.710 --> 00:01:52.080
the distributive property to

29
00:01:52.104 --> 00:01:55.786
factor the expression three times x plus 12.

30
00:01:57.639 --> 00:01:59.260
What is the greatest common factor

31
00:01:59.284 --> 00:02:01.284
of the two terms in this expression?

32
00:02:05.856 --> 00:02:10.150
The greatest common factor of three times x and 12 is three.

33
00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:16.570
So we can rewrite each term as three times something.

34
00:02:19.710 --> 00:02:21.740
Then we can apply the distributive property.

35
00:02:25.623 --> 00:02:29.180
This expression, three times the quantity x plus four

36
00:02:29.420 --> 00:02:31.310
is equivalent to the original one.

37
00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:36.859
The factored expression represents

38
00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:40.159
the area of the mural as a product of two factors.

39
00:02:43.519 --> 00:02:47.340
So another possible set of dimensions of the mural could be

40
00:02:47.440 --> 00:02:50.689
three meters long and x plus four meters tall.

41
00:02:53.139 --> 00:02:54.320
Now you know how to use

42
00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:58.260
the distributive property to both expand and factor expressions.